animal.description:
Meet Lady Lu!

Wendy & Lady Lu came to us after their pet parent passed away. They are bonded siblings looking for a FURever home together. We will only be accepting applications for families willing to adopt them both.

Lady Lu is a follower, she does whatever her sister Wendy does, and is passive about everything. She will be the first to come ask you for pets and scratches once she warms up to her nee people. This lady says standing to eat is overrated, so she hold her bowl between her feet while she lays down to eat. She loves her sister Wendy more than life itself, and she is so happy they are going to get a new home together! 

Nickname: The Golden Girls
Age: Wendy (9) & Lady Lu (8)
Breed: Border Collie
Weight: 55 lbs/each
Foster home: Madison, WI
Activity level: Medium
Sleep style: Couch or dog bed
Snore-o-meter: 0
Bark-o-meter: 4 (alert barking but they quiet down quickly with the word “hush”)
Fashion: Bandana
Favorite season: Winter
Commands: Come, sit, wait, off, leave it, down, fetch, kennel
Walk out song: Poker Face ~Lady GaGa
Personality: Affectionate, Friendly, Energetic, Confident, Intelligent, Eager, Alert, Loyal & Outdoorsy
Best features: Expressive eyes and the softest fur
Friendly with all: dogs, kids, cats
Loves: Hiking in the snow, car rides, chasing squirrels, bird-watching, gnawing bones, playing fetch, long winter’s naps, snuffle mats, patrolling the yard, getting butt scratches, backyard bonfires, getting brushed & going on adventures 
Bucket List: Paddleboarding, camping, chasing you while you sled down a hill & dog agility competition.

*Wendy & Lady Lu are wicked smart, working breed dogs. They will thrive with an active family who will provide them with physical exercise/structure and plenty of mental stimulation/enrichment.

To read more about Wendy, please click here: https://www.petfinder.com/dog/wendy-50392165/wi/whitewater/alberts-dog-lounge-wi506/

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $500 for a bonded pair.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

Wendy & Lady Lu came to us after their pet parent passed away. They are bonded siblings looking for a FURever home together. We will only be accepting applications for families willing to adopt them both.

Wendy is a leader of the group, the more assertive one of the pair. You can be sure if these girls are going something, Wendy promted the activity. Wendy diagnosed epilepsy and takes a daily prescription to control her seizures. Her pills are given with breakfast and dinner. She is super stoked for her and Lady Lu to find their forever home together!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Meet Buddy, a painfully shy 3 year-old Husky/Beagle mix male who's looking for a quiet home where he can truly relax and enjoy life. This little guy came into an overcrowded county dog shelter and was very frightened there. He made the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could take his time finding the perfect new home. We don't have any history on Buddy's pre-shelter life but he is extremely shy when meeting new people and in new situations. Buddy is very comfortable around other dogs though so he is going to need a home where he'll have a canine buddy who will show him the ropes and help boost his confidence when he's uncertain about things. Although it takes him awhile to warm up to new people, Buddy is a great friend once he's comfortable with someone. He's very friendly and affectionate with his foster mom and loves to give lots of kisses. Buddy is still very unsure of himself on a leash and tends to stick close to his handler making it very difficult to walk with him. Having a canine walking buddy will help him in this area as well as he begins to realize how enjoyable walking on a leash is. Given his shyness, Buddy is going to need a home in a quiet neighborhood with a yard that has a secure aboveground fence. Urban or high-density suburban living would be very frightening for him. We're looking forward to seeing this sweet boy thrive and blossom in his new home! Buddy weighs about 32 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Buddy. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Buddy and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Sissy  is a 2 year old Great Dane looking for her forever home. She is 80 pounds  and has the longest legs!  No cats for this girl, but she is good with dogs after slow introductions.  She is great with er humans!. At least a 6 foot fence for her .  If you are interested in learning more about Sissy, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Booker loves treats and is very treat motivated, he is also leash trained for the most part but could still use a little extra training there. animal.description:
Personality: Comet is a fun, energetic, playful & goofy boy. He is very social and is wiggly when meeting new people. He likes the outdoors and enjoys going on long walks and runs. He would benefit from daily physical and mental exercise. He would do well with a family that has some herding breed experience. He also loves going to the beach and playing in the sand. As energetic as he is, Comet also loves to curl up and relax with you. He is very intelligent and easy to train. He picks up commands quickly and is already good with the basics. Comet did well in his foster home with a routine potty schedule. He also did well getting left alone when provided exercises and had his bed and chew toys to keep him occupied. My care has been sponsored by Pallavi Akella!

History: Comet came to us from the central valley. 

Dog Skills/Cat Skills: Comet is a very excitable dog, that he can be to forward for more reserved and shy dogs who prefer space and time to warm up. Comet tends to be vocal and bossy in play with dogs, and will pick on less confident dogs. Comet does enjoy chase and physical contact play, but has shown to escalate corrections from other dogs. He may do best as an only dog, but has also shown to tolerate and play with females that are calm, social, polite, and playful, who can tolerate his very vocal, pushy play style. At this time comet has shown to only do well meeting other dogs on a loose leash walk, before being able to play. Comet has shown hyper focus on cats, and adopters should be aware of breed tendencies.


Leash Skills: Comet pulls while walking on a leash and would benefit from the use of a front clipping harness. 

Ready to meet Comet? Fill out the form to request an appointment Primary Color: White Secondary Color: Red Weight: 48.4lbs Age: 3yrs 1mths 0wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Phantom was aptly named because of her striking blue eye.  Isn't she gorgeous?  And this girl has a gorgeous spirit about her when you know all she's been through.  This girl came to us having had surgery to repair a broken hip and broken legs (probably due to being hit by a car).  Somehow the vet decided not to spay her though and, lo and behold, a month later she was back at a vet to have an emergency c-section because she was in labor!  Thank God there were only three BIG pups and they were all healthy!  Can you imagine her pushing big pups out a broken pelvis???

Well, now that the pups are old enough to find new families, and her bones are healed, this beauty is ready for a new home of her own.  

Phantom is a sweet and gentle soul that wants to please people  We believe she has some Aussie in her and maybe Tibetan Spaniel but really don't know.  Whatever she is, she is beautiful in side and out.  

If you are looking for a beautiful and gentle soul that just wants to make you happy then Phantom may be the dog you're looking for.  Read on or go to the adoptiin process page of our website, throwmeabonedogrescue.org, to apply.  

All potential adopters are expected to complete an application and provide pictures of their yard, patio, and/or balcony making sure we can see the fence line and/or railing.  The application can be completed and submitted from our website - throwmeabonedogrescue.org - the link is found of the Adoption Process page.  Applications will be reviewed for approval before setting an appointment to come meet and possibly adopt the dog of interest.  In addition, those who live in a rental property are expected to provide proof that they are allowed to have a dog where they live.

Each of our rescued dogs has been de-wormed if necessary, de-flea'd (with topical treatment if old enough, and by medicated bath if too young), spayed/neutered, microchipped, is up to date on shots, and has been fully examined by a veterinarian.  In addition, each adopted dog comes with a starter baggie of the food it has been eating, a few treats for training purposes, a rawhide chew, a lead and collar, and a folder containing pertinent records.

animal.description: A398557 Dalton Lab Mix Neutered Male 2 Years Did somebody say snacks?? Dalton is a gorgeous boy with a huge personality. This 2-year-old lab mix still acts like a wild puppy and is looking for someone with the time, patience, and experience to help him be successful. Dalton has started positive reinforcement training at the shelter, and hes working on potty training, leash skills, remaining calm around other dogs, and manners overall. Dalton is incredibly food motivated, so hell be a fun dog for an adopter who is committed to treat-based training. He also loves toys and bones, but he can be a bit intense around his prized possessions, so he would greatly benefit from working on trade and drop it. Because of this intensity and his other training needs, Dalton would do best as an only pet in a home without young kids. If youre looking for an affectionate, active project dog, Dalton could be the one for you! Do you think youre ready to take on this crazy goofball?

animal.description: Introducing her grace, Lady Daphne Bridgerton! This gorgeous gal is an NYC native rescued from our friends at the ACC, and is about 1 year old. As a young husky mix, Daphne definitely needs an adopter prepared to put serious work intro training and make sure she has lots of mental and physical stimulation. She is very smart and is improving with house-breaking and leash walking, but will need to continue working on these with her adopter. She is a high energy lady and is happiest with several exercise sessions a day, and a structured environment in the home. Daphne is very friendly and has so far loved every person and dog she's met! She needs to work on not jumping up to say hi and containing her excitement when she meets a new person. With a regular exercise and training routine, she'll be a wonderful companion for an active adopter! Approved adopters interested in Daphne can email adopt@heartsandbonesrescue.com for more info. If you're not approved yet, apply today at heartsandbonesrescue.com.

animal.description:
Patches was originally transferred to THS from the Lucas County Canine Care and Control, where she was there for over a year during a pending court case with her previous owner. She spent some time in foster and her family had nothing but wonderful things to say about her! Patches loves people, and is a huge couch potato! She snorts like a pig when sniffing around on walks, and even snores! Patches is a people person, and needs to go home as an only pet as she is not friendly with other animals. She was able to spend this holiday season in a home with multiple family members that ranged in age from 9-18. She adored everyone, and really enjoyed snuggling up to all of her new friends!

For 2021, Patches has made it her personal goal to not only find her forever family, but look good doing it! Her foster mom worked hard on cutting back on her food, and took her on regular walks. After she's done exercising, Patches enjoys cuddling up at her foster mom's feet while she works! 

Patches was brought back to THS recently because her new family was unable to care for her, so at no fault of her own! Ready for her second chance, Patches is still looking for the perfect fit! Could it be you??

Email foster@toledohumane.org if you're interested in adopting!

animal.description:
KRAMER - ID#A045413

Hi! My name is KRAMER. I am a neutered male, buff and white Affenpinscher mix. The shelter staff think I am about 5 years old. I have been at the shelter since Jan 12, 2021.

I LOVE TO: play with toys and hang out!
I HAVE: an average activity level and would be great in a home with another dog of my size
I GET ALONG WELL WITH: families with kids
I WOULD RATHER NOT: be left alone outside, I'm too small
I NEED: some training and socialization skills
I AM: a very sweet dog!

Starting the Adoption Process

Thank you for your interest in adopting an animal…..to begin the process you will need to access & submit an adoption application. 

You can access our adoption application at either, Petprojectfoundation.org or on the City of San Clemente’s website, under the Animal Services option.  An adoption application can be submitted to the shelter, via Fax at (949) 366-4765, via email to Animalservices@scdpanimalshelter.org, or dropped off at the shelter in the drop box, located by our front door.  The San Clemente – Dana Point Animal Shelter is located at 221 Avenida Fabricante in San Clemente.

We look forward to receiving your application and will be in contact with you via email.

The shelter is currently closed to walk-in public, due to the COVID-19 virus. 

Staff are on site during our regular business hours (below), to address phone calls,  offer shelter services by appointment only, as well as handle any/all animal control concerns.

Our regular business hours are as follows: 

Monday – Closed

Tuesday – 10-4

Wednesday – 10-4

Thursday – 10-4

Friday – 10-4

Saturday – 10-4

Sunday – 12-3

In person services are by appointment only, due to the COVID-19 virus, please contact the shelter at (949) 492-1617, for more information.

animal.description:
Pepper comes to us from Inland Valley Humane Shelter. She is a big strong girl who is full of energy and loves to run and play! This young girl loves people but would need to be the only animal in the home as she was never properly socialized or trained. Pepper would benefit from an experienced owner who can provide training and structure to this diamond in the rough.

Please note that only experienced dog owners and homes with no children or other pets will be considered as she is high-energy and dog/cat reactive. 

Check out the video of Pepper from a recent play session! Meet her at our Costa Mesa location.

---
We know there are some 3rd party websites giving mis-information on the location of the pet you may be interested in. For correct information, please visit the location of the animal's name listed directly after their name, and visit the bio for more information. Thank you!! (Ex: "Sparky - Chino Hills Location will mean you go to Chino Hills; "Fluffy - Claremont Location will mean you go to Claremont; and "Fido - Costa Mesa Location will mean you go to Costa Mesa) There may also be mis-information about the status of an available pet. If the animal is no longer listed on our main website, it is no longer available for adoption. For accurate information please visit pricelesspetrescue.org

animal.description:
LEARNING TO TRUST:  2 years old / 20 lbs. 

Hi, my name’s Lynley! I had a home, but there were simply too many dogs in the home for us to all get the love, socialization, and attention we deserve, so Mostly Mutts is helping me find new families to love and be loved by!     

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  There were several dogs in my previous home, and I came in with two other dogs who have already been adopted, and we get along fine.  Otherwise, I haven’t really cared for the dogs I’ve met at MM’s, though I’m new and it’s a bit overwhelming, so if you have a dog at home already, let’s meet / My previous owner reported that I got along fine with cats, so if you have a dog-friendly kitty, let’s meet / I haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts, and I would not like kids to run up to me or pick me up until I really trusted them, so if you have much older calm kids, let’s meet.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  Initially, I was very skittish and did not want to leave my room at all.  The shelter volunteers began to work their magic – sitting with me, spending time with me and letting me set the pace for interaction.  I’ve begun to warm up and build my trust in people…even nudging them for nice pettings now and following them a bit.  My loving side is emerging, and I am even learning about toys and having a lot of fun with them!  I just need a patient family that will give me a little time to know that they will love me, and I’ll return the love.  If I’m rushed, I may give a little growl and show my teeth, just to tell you to slow down / My former owner said I was ‘high energy’, but the volunteers who care for me say I have more of a medium energy level (4-6).

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am now a student in the Mostly Mutts University training program, where I am learning lots of great doggie commands with my trainer.  So far, I have mastered ‘sit’ and ‘come’.  I walk well on my leash and - right now, we are working on building my confidence outside of my kennel.  I am gaining more confidence every day, and just love my training sessions and the time I get to spend with my trainer, so check back to see my progress / I was not crated in my former home, and my crate manners are good at Mostly Mutts, as I am venturing out of my room more and more.  My room is my safe spot so I may want a crate in my new home / Since getting used to going outside, my potty habits have been good on the shelter schedule.  I was reportedly potty trained in my former home, so hopefully that will be the case in my new home.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I just love playing with toys – I don’t know if I knew what they were, but I do now!  Once I know you are my friend, I enjoy cuddles and neck rubs.   I am also finding out that I like laps.  I warm up quickest to quiet natured people.  Bits of Pup-peronis in my food has made it tastier for me / I have not been crazy about walking on the grass while on my walks, and my trainer is working with me on this.

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed. I have a cute half tail – I think I was born that way.

I am looking for patient and calm natured family who will continue to help me grow my trust in a wonderful home!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
‘BOND’ THEMED MOMMA:  5 years old / 49 lbs. 

Hi, my name is Moneypenny – momma to the ‘Bond’ themed puppies who have all been adopted!  I was at animal control – pregnant and heartworm positive with cherry eye.  I needed a hero, Mostly Mutts became just that and rescued me.  I went to a great foster home, where I gave birth to and raised my puppies.  Now, it’s my turn to find a great family to love! 

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  I’ve had mixed interactions with the dogs in my previous foster home where I raised my babies.  Perhaps my hormones were still high from pregnancy and nursing, so I would need a meet and greet to see if we will be friends if there is another dog in my prospective home / Cats unknown / I also haven’t met kids yet at Mostly Mutts, so let’s meet and best no toddlers that I may bump over.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a loving girl who is very social with my people.  My former foster describes me as an ‘amazing’ dog.  I have a very expressive face and it seems I am smiling when I am happy – so cute!  I am affectionate and readily seek out attention. I am a bit playful too / My current energy level is about 3-5, but that will likely increase after my heartworm treatment is completed.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY:  I am now in the Mostly Mutts University training program and am a pretty smart gal.  I have already learned the following skills: ‘sit’, ‘down’, and ‘come’.  I will occasionally give my paw too.  Since I am a treat fan, I bet you can reinforce these skills and teach me even more / My crate manners are good at the shelter.  I did not use a crate in my foster home, since I had my puppies / I used pee pads in my foster home initially, as I did not like going outside, but after a little while I eventually started going out on a good schedule and I’m doing pretty well on the shelter schedule too, so – keep me on a good schedule so my potty skills will be reinforced in my new home. 

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love people and attention - especially belly rubs (and usually will roll over for one as soon as I am outside).  I have discovered tennis balls but don’t play with them much yet since I do need to stay calmer until after my heartworm treatment is completed. I tend to play independently or enjoy spending time chewing on nice bone.  Food and treats are also on my ‘favorites’ list / I don’t like to be left alone, as I am a real people dog.  Initially, I was not crazy about going outside, so I may need encouragement in this area in my new home.

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.  Unfortunately, my previous owner did not keep me on a monthly heartworm preventative, so I am heartworm positive.  Mostly Mutts will cover the cost of my treatment with their vet, so local adoption only. I’ve had my cherry eye surgery now, so I have a couple of weeks of eye meds and wearing a cone and I should be good in that area.

I am looking for a loving family to give me a wonderful home!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Male Treeing Walker Coonhound and Black and Tan Coonhound Mix

Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Approximate date of birth: 01/17/2018

Weight: 45.5 lbs

Children: Unknown 

Dogs: Yes, but he's selective 

Cats: Unknown


Arrow has a ton of energy and absolutely loves to run. We are pretty sure he was a cheetah in a past life! He was found as a stray and brought to a humane society that we work with and we're so happy we could take him in. 

A home with a large fenced in yard would be ideal for this energetic boy. Leash walks are great, but he will also need plenty of space to zoom around unleashed and burn off energy. His tail is super long and he wags it in a propeller-like motion. This may be how he reaches hypersonic speed! When he is out and about his mind is focused on playing and running, so he has no time for cuddles. Once he's relaxed and has gotten some energy out, he wants to rest on your lap to get some love and attention. 

With the number 74 branded on both sides, it's likely he was a working dog and that explains why he enjoys running in our fields so much. The brands are starting to fade, but his desire to run is still strong and his heart is full of happiness with each stride he takes. 

Does this flying Arrow sound like the one you've been dreaming of?

animal.description:
Lucy is a young 1-2 yr old Wire Hair Terrier Mix that was dumped at a lawn care company in Central Louisiana. She was very leary to come to the people trying to rescue her but we soon found that she was highly food motivated.  Lucy has to build your trust and is initially standoffish of you. She will need you to let her come to you and when she’s ready she will be in your lap.  Reaching down or towards her from a standing position frightens her , again until she is trusting. She was heartworm positive and had to go through treatment. She was negative for microfillaria and received a Proheart 12.   She does not like her mouth bothered so she was given her meds via canned puppy food.  I tried to get her DNA from her mouth and lost her trust for a few days and she didn’t want to be held by me.  She loves soft food but will also eat kibbles.  She has a hefty appetite and has gained a couple of pounds.  She has been in a foster home with 5 other dogs for 3 months. She particularly likes playing with a much bigger 8 month old cur pup and they play tug-a-war, wrestle, and chase toys. She seems much more comfortable with men but will be a lap baby with the female foster and slowly trusting. She loves belly and chest rubs in your lap. She will be best in a home with no kids or older dog savvy teens. 

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

animal.description:
Meet Reba! 

Reba is a beautiful girl with the sweetest personality! Coming in at 125lbs, she is a big girl with lots of love to give! She was surrendered to our rescue after her owner died. Reba has lived with other dogs, but like most Saint Bernards, she loves her personal space and really would love to be the queen of her own castle. She is excellent with children who are old enough that they will not get knocked down. animal.description:
One year old Clarice is from southern IL and she is happy to be up here in hopes of finding her forever home! In the meantime, she is having a ball in her foster home! Her foster mom had never even had a dog before, so when she signed up to foster and ended up with Clarice, we hoped it would be a good match! Her foster mom has done so great with her and loves this girl so much. She calls her Lola though. 
She took the time to tell us alllll about Clarice, the good and the quirks:
"Lola loves toys (especially squeaky ones) and balls. She also enjoys playing tug-of-war, running, and going for long walks (hold on tight because she can really pull when chasing bunnies and squirrels)! Lola is very curious and stops to smell everything. Playing in the snow is also favorite pastime of hers. Lola loves people and always wants to be where the action is. Body massages are her favorite and she loves sprawling out on everyone's bed. Lola is very motivated by treats, praise and attention. She also prefers toilet water to water in her water dish, so keep the lid down. Lola likes to jump up on people to say hello, but we try to discourage that. 
Lola doesn't like being alone and she hasn't been alone yet in our home. She is slowly getting used to the crate, but still in the dislike category. She will settle down in the crate after 10-30 minutes, though. Lola is housebroken if kept on a schedule. 
On walks, Lola will pull but her harness is helpful! She must still be getting used to the non-rural environment because is fascinated by moving vehicles and will often bark at trucks. She will bark at other dogs on a walk sometimes, but we think that she really wants to say hi and play. She is still just a pup. I am trying to teach her how to heel, which she is beginning to learn as long as there are not other distractions.
Lola loves toys so much. Toys are the most fun if she has someone to play with. Balls, tugging toys, squeaking toys, frozen kongs, etc. 
Overall, Lola is a great dog. She is very smart and enjoys pleasing people. She responds well to treats and attention. She loves to snuggle up with us. Lola is very curious and will stop to smell everything. Since she is so strong, you'll need to hold on tight when she sees or smells a bunny. Mealtime is her favorite time of day. She is quite lovable and keeps us laughing."

Lola can be jumpy and slightly mouthy in a puppy way, so we would feel most comfortable with adults or a family with older kids. A strong handler for walks and someone with an aptitude and desire to seek training for their new dog would also be ideal! We hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
Miss Figgy is a 9 year old Female Boxer Shepherd mix. She was surrendered to a local shelter two days before Christmas because her family was moving.
She is happy, vibrant, and has a medium energy level.
She loves dogs of all ages, and sizes. She is cat friendly as well.
She is completely housebroken and loves her crate. Older children may be best as she is a larger girl of 75 pounds.
She is quiet on a leash. She does not react to other animals, or people.  She is protective of her people, and her yard. She will bark to alert strangers of her presence.
She is a big cuddle bug. Above all else this girl loves to eat.  
Unfortunately Figgy was not spayed at a younger age, probably had multiple litters of puppies in her life, and had breast tumors that were surgically removed when she was spayed under our care.
The tissue was sent off for possible pathology and it was determined to be adenocarcinoma. The margins indicated that this cancer had spread beyond the initial mass in her breast. The tumors have been removed but there is a chance they may come back. Therefore we are looking for a loving home to give her the best life possible and shower her with tons of love. We are unsure what amount of life she has left, could be shortened, could be longer. Figgy is fostered in Hickory and can’t wait to meet you and fall in love.

Bella needs a home without cats. 

Bella Notte came to us from Hitchcock Road Animal Services after being surrendered by her owners.

animal.description:
Looks like: Poodle
Male, 11 years old, 12 pounds
Georgie is a handsome boy. He is a friendly little guy and is content finding a soft place to sleep and relax. He likes getting cookies, doesn't mind being held and is friendly with other dogs. He is very vocal and his future person will have to be accepting of this. He will become talkative at new things, people and noises. He's just sounding an alert, as he responds in a friendly way to new things. He is not a good apartment dog as he does not want to be alone in the house or in the car and will let it be know by barking incessantly, and even howling at times. Someone willing to help him with this separation anxiety and willing to spend more time than not with him, is ideal. 

While on leash, he walks very quickly, pulls a little, but responds decently. He mostly wants brisk walks but will occasionally stop short and cuts across one's path. He will also stop and look at any dogs that come near but he prefers not to engage. With new people, he is a little distant, willing to meet adults and allows a sniff of the hand and a brief pet. While home, he likes to explore the house and yard but does not have interest in playing. Georgie is not crazy about car travel, although he jumps in as if it's a natural thing to do. Then whimpers or whines a little. Sometimes he quiets down, and curls into his car bed. 

Since Georgie is deaf, it is necessary to communicate with him visually. He seems to be quick to learn the territory--the doors, the furniture. He is very self-consoling and does not beg for attention. Georgie needs a quiet home with one or two adults, might be fine with other small dogs since he previously lived with two others. 

Georgie's guardian's home tragically burned down in the recent fires in Santa Cruz. His senior guardian decided moving into an assisted living facility would be her next step so she had somewhere to live, and unfortunately couldn't take Georgie with her. He was adopted from POMDR and unfortunately it did not work out due to an intense bladder stone complicating his health. This has been treated but he is susceptible to urinary crystals and will need future monitoring and care. He also has a heart murmur and will be on heart medication for life.

animal.description:
*Old Dogs New Digs is assisting Baxter’s current owners in rehoming. He is currently in a private home. 

Baxter is an 8 year old, 80#, Olde English Bulldog. Baxter has some anxiety and the unpredictable behavior of young children are just too much for him. He is looking for a quieter home where he can relax and enjoy the company of a loving adult or two. He would do well with respectful teens. He is currently on medication for his anxiety, but his owner thinks he could likely be weaned off once in a quieter environment. 

Baxter is a loving, somewhat goofy fellow who doesn’t require a lot of exercise to be content. A short daily walk would be plenty. He does pull a bit on leash, so his person needs to be able to handle that. He has a little arthritis in his hips and is on a supplement for that. 

Baxter would ideally like a fenced yard as he tends to follow his nose and may wander where it leads him! Baxter loves car rides. He is also totally housetrained with never an accident in the home. 

Baxter will be happiest being an only dog. He loves his people, but is not really looking for a canine companion.  He’s had no experience living with cats or other small animals. 

Baxter has intermittent skin issues which can lead to ear infections, so diet is important to keep those issues at bay. He does quite well on his Wellness kibble formula. 

If you see a forever friend in Baxter’s soulful eyes, please do submit an adoption survey here for consideration. 

https://www.olddogsnewdigs.com/adoption-survey/

Adoption Fee:  $75.00

If interested you MUST complete the Adoption Application:  http://fuzzypawzrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application-2/

Casper is a shy 10-year-old Chihuahua who wants to be your cuddle buddy; this handsome little guy came to Fuzzy Pawz Rescue after his owner passed away. 

To say he loves his people is an understatement; he follows his foster mom around to see what she is doing and sits on her lap the second she sits down. He likes cuddling under blankets while you are gone and hasn’t chewed anything he wasn’t supposed to. He is mostly housetrained but does need someone to remind him to go out every couple of hours until he gets in a routine. 

Casper barks at any outside noises even from under the covers in bed with us at night. He is not great on leash because he is shy of new people/experiences, but we think he would enjoy learning to be more of an on-the-go dog. He tolerates our other foster dogs, big and small, but he doesn’t really like them and growls if they come too close to his cuddle buddy. He has lived with cats peacefully in the past. He is looking for a home without children under 15 as they scare him.

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Pepper and I just turned one year on January 9th. I had a home and like so many dogs I lost my home because my family didn’t train me when I was a puppy. Puppy behaviors became less amusing to them as I became an adult but I didn’t know what I was even doing wrong. Ironically I know all the commands, sit, down, come. I just get excited.

So now I need a family that will give me love and show me what behaviors they want from me. Positive reinforcement works best with me. I’m a petite girl, my mom was a pure bred staffy bull and I weigh under 50 pounds. I love people and do well with other dogs but will only be placed as an opposite sex placement.

If you are looking for a beautiful, spirited, happy, smaller girl, I am the one! If you want to meet me please fill out the application. I am a cross post for another rescue , but everyone loves me so much they are helping!


Pepper will only be placed into a forever home that is located within 1.5 hours of Lake & McHenry Counties in Illinois...(sorry, NO exceptions).**

If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an application:at www.aandsrescue.com/AdoptionApplication100109.doc

Once your completed application is received, it will be reviewed, and then a volunteer will contact you.

*We cannot do anything until we receive your completed application*

Mike is a lovable galumph of a 2 yo German Shepherd. In the short time he’s been in foster care he’s picked up a bunch of new skills. He can sit, go down, leave it, and ring a bell to go outside. He loves to play fetch and chase teenage boys around the house. He’ll thrive and delight in a family situation with some training to deal with his teenage moodiness around other dogs. He’s a total sweetheart adored by his foster family who would love to keep him but are moving from a house with a yard to a condo.

Mike is best in a home with no dogs, even though he has made dog friends, he can get grumpy and not want to play. German Shepherds are really smart and being he is young, he has so much potential. Mike is a doll, but will need continuing training and someone who has experience with this breed.

We don't know how he is with cats and prefer a home without to be safe. :) 

** WANT MORE INFO OR THINKING OF ADOPTING THIS PET? **

For a QUICK RESPONSE go to -- WWW.HOPALONG.ORG -- and complete an adoption application. It is not a commitment to adopt, it just begins the process and shows interest in a particular animal. animal.description:
Meet BLAZE!
-Male
-Approximately 1 year old
-Husky MIX

Blaze is:
-Energetic
-Playful
-Anxious
-Vocal
-Loving
-Friendly
-Active
-Curious
-Potty trained
-AMAZING with dogs
-Great with kids
-Does NOT do well with CATS!!

Blaze is the biggest goofball you will ever meet! He has a silly personality and is always looking to put a smile on his family's face. He LOVES his fursibiling SO much!! He can run and play all day with them! He absolutely loves the attention and feeling love from his humans. He loves his people so much, that when you leave he will get VERY sad. He is a smart, but stubborn pup. He knows sit, paw and other paw. He has excellent recall skills, just needs someone to continue working training with him. 

Blaze is the pawwwwwfect dog for someone who works from home even after COVID. He likes to be with people at all times. Because of the constant changes in his short life, he suffers from SEVERE anxiety, With this being said, he will need a professional crate when and if you were to leave to run errands. Every time you step out of the home, he thinks you are never coming back so he will go through all obstacles to get back in your arms.

Blaze's ideal home would be:
-An ACTIVE family
-A FENCED in yard (A MUST!!)
-A home with another dog!!!!
-Someone who is willing to train

animal.description:
Charlee, 4 year old terrier blend, 45lbs. Up to date on vaccinations and microchipped. 3 legs. 

Here is her story. In 2017 Charlee came to Paws Humane with a severely broken leg. Our vet determined that it was too severe to repair so we amputated. She recovered really well and was adopted shortly after. The person who adopted her wanted to return her for puppy like behaviors but never showed up to do so. Recently she was surrendered to another shelter by her owner who had found her wandering 2 years ago and kept her.  My guess is that her adopter just let her go some where instead of doing the right thing. Then the woman who kept dumped her at the shelter when she also didn't want anything more to do with her. She is sweet and we can not find a reason why no one wants this girl. We know that she lived with a child and cat in her previous home but she does not seem to do well with other dogs.

1. This rescue is run out of a private home please do not email asking to meet the dog unless you have an application submitted or you have an application that has been approved 6months or less
2.  The information that we have is current and to the best of our knowledge when we learn more about the dog's personality we immediately post that.
3.   All of our dogs are good with school-age children. And will do fine with that as long as your child is good and respects dogs boundaries
4. Please visit our Facebook page. Pictures and updates are posted there first.  

5. All of our rescue dogs have the following

Spay or neuter certificates

vaccination records including Rabies

Are on a monthly flea and heartworm preventive. 

Crate leash and house trained. 

Get along with other dogs ( otherwise indicated )

Enjoy the company of school-age children who are respectful to them 

Most of them enjoy the company of cats as well, HOWEVER, in the past, we have found out that for some reason that is not always the case.  

We work VERY hard making sure our dogs acclimate to their new homes.  We seek adopters whose current pets are current on vaccinations and are altered. {

PLEASE do not fill out an application if your pets are not. You will be denied.


Applications can be found by going to our website  www.laurashoperescue.com

animal.description:
Maynard is a very sweet, loving boy who enjoys all people and dogs he meets. He is great with kids - playful but gentle and enjoys following them around the house. He does great in the crate overnight and has quickly figured out house training. He’s beginning to master some simple commands like sit, down, and wait. (The latter is challenging for him!)

He enjoys time outside, but he’s still learning how to walk on a leash. He requires some patience on his walk as he explores the sights and smells and will refuse to move if you push him too quickly. Each day, he’s willing to walk a bit farther and faster with more confidence so this may resolve with regular walks, consistency, and comfort.

He enjoys chewing so giving him ample things to chew would be advised. He’s a medium energy dog - he can be playful but mellows out fairly quickly for a dog his age. He doesn't bother our chickens which may bode well for any feline families! 

** WANT MORE INFO OR THINKING OF ADOPTING THIS PET? **

For a QUICK RESPONSE go to -- WWW.HOPALONG.ORG -- and complete an adoption application. It is not a commitment to adopt, it just begins the process and shows interest in a particular animal. Someone will contact you by phone or email within 2 full business days to interview you or inform you on the status of your application.

animal.description:
Foster location:  Boise ID
Breed:  Chihuahua
Age:  13(ish)
Adoption Fee:  $50.00
Spayed, Vaccinated, Microchipped

If interested you MUST complete the Adoption Application:  http://fuzzypawzrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application-2/

Are you looking for a little lap dog? Sissy is your girl!

Sissy is a 13 year old Chihuahua who came to Fuzzy Pawz Rescue after her owner passed away. As she came into her foster home she was a bit shy and just wanted to curl up on anyone’s lap for comfort. Since then she has won the hearts over many! 

She is such a sweet girl who only wants you to love her and let her snuggle on your lap. In return she will shower you with kisses. She likes to take short walks and loves to go on car rides together but prefers to sit nicely on your lap. She loves to be your shadow as you go about the house and even in the yard. You see, Sissy was a lucky girl who was not only loved by her previous owner as well as her foster family but she has always had a person at home. 

She doesn’t mind you being gone for a few hours but she does have some separation anxiety because she loves being with people. At night, not only does she insist on sleeping with you, but will bury herself under your covers and snore away. Sissy does well with other dogs her size as long as they are calm and not in her face. The same said about cats. She of course wouldn’t mind being the only dog either so she doesn’t have to share your attention. Sissy loves the attention from everyone but would do best in a quieter home. If there are kids in the home, they must be 15 or older.

Being that she is a senior, she has some lumps that are just fatty tissue that older dogs usually get. She had a full senior physical at the vet and as she is in good health overall, there are a few things that need to be watched. The vets suspect she has the starts of cataracts in her right eye. As of now she doesn’t seem to have any issues with it. She also has a weakened trachea. With this, we just don’t want to do anything to cause her to cough a lot. For example, don’t spray fragrance in the air if she is in the same room, don’t use the powders on your carpets before you vacuum and don’t take her for a walk where the dirt and dust can affect her nasal passage. And if you take her for a walk she will need to be in a harness rather than the leash attached to her collar. A smoke free home is a must for. She also recently had her dental done so her teeth are nice and clean! 

Sissy is a special girl who deserves to live out her golden years in a home where she is pampered and loves to the fullest!
animal.name: Sissy

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Lyla! My best physical characteristics are my ears, face markings, and my front legs that dance when I'm excited! My foster mom loves how I dance and prance on my front legs when I'm happy. I also love to come onto the couch and rub my face on your face before I start playing with my foster brother and sister. I also will kiss you right in your mouth!

I hear I wasn't very well taken care of before I came to my foster home, but it doesn't reflect on how I interact with my foster family - I love my 8-year-old foster brother and 7-year-old foster sister - they play with me so much and it's pretty much the best thing ever!

I am potty and kennel trained! I reluctantly sleep in a kennel at night, but I have a really comfy bed in my kennel that I curl up into. I know drop it, sit, go get it, no, leave it, go potty, go outside, play and sooooo many other things! I have not taken any training courses yet, but I am pretty well trained, as I am a wise gal. Love from my humans and treats are all the motivation I need. I am pretty calm most of the time but I get really excited when I'm playing with toys with my humans, I love to play. A squeaky ball is my favorite, tug-of-war with a rope is fun - basically any toy is my favorite!

I didn't live with children before until I got to my foster home but Lexi (7) and Jaiden (8) have shown me that kids are so amazing to play with - I follow Jaiden around a lot to play and I love to snuggle Lexi on the couch. I have not met a cat or small animals. I would probably be super curious at first, but I'm pretty gentle and when I'm told no, I listen. I live with two other dogs - Simba (a Volpino) and Belle (a Chihuahua/Dachshund). They are much smaller than me, I try really hard to play with them, but they are a little scared of me. I would just love to roll around with them! I understand that when another dog says "no" I need to stop.

My foster mom tells me that even though I was not well taken care of, I am one of the best dogs she has had. I love everyone around me, I interact with new dogs well, I walk pretty, I play nice, and I was kennel trained within a couple days. My foster mom tells me she loves me a lot so that's awesome!

In my forever, I would really love to have another dog that plays gently and knows when to stop. Kids would be a really nice plus because I love children so much. My dream day would consist of playing, snuggling, going outside, repeat. Would love to meet you! 2/2/21 3:35 PM

animal.description:
TO MEET Oreo, PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION TO ADOPT AT www.almosthomeyyc.com.

*PLEASE NOTE WE ARE LOCATED IN CANADA AND UNABLE TO ADOPT TO ANOTHER COUNTRY.

INFORMATION: Oreo is a 4 year old Husky mix that was surrendered. She has beautiful blue eyes and loves the outdoors.

TEMPERAMENT: Oreo loves other dogs and loves being outside. She does have some food aggressions that will need to be worked on. She walks vey well on leash but is not a big fan of the slip lead or a lot of touching around her head and neck. Oreo travels very well in the car and has good recall if there aren't too many distractions. She loves to sit quietly in the window and watch cars, people and dogs walk by. Oreo has been working on learning to trust people and is doing very well with it. She will seek out affection but is still nervous of the response she will receive from her person. 


IDEAL HOME: Oreo is best suited for an active household, one where she can spend plenty of time exploring the outdoors, she would be an amazing hiking partner. Oreo is a pack dog and she would thrive in a home with another dog. She also would like someone that is patient and will help her rebuild her trust in people. 

If you would like to meet Oreo, please fill in an adoption application.

Please note: We apologize for being unable to respond to inquiries about our dogs without an adoption application.

animal.description: Jane is a 3-4 year old Collie mix. She sits next to her person without being called. She likes to give gentle chin nudges. Jane is high energy so this gal would need plenty of playtime and exercise. She pulls on a leash but with some basic obedience training, this could easily be resolved. Jane is food motivated. She knows the sit command. Jane is afraid of cats in a shelter atmosphere. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. MEET-AND-GREET REQUIRED Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.joplinhumane.org. We are the Joplin Humane Society in Joplin, Missouri. 417-623-3642

animal.description:
MEET MAKO!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. She is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4506680.

Mako is such a sweet girl that has been at the shelter for a long time and she needs to go home soon!! She's been there over 60 days but that doesn't get her down. She loves when volunteers come to her kennel to take her for a walk. She walks easily on the leash but she does zig zag back and forth when walking and she loves people so much that she likes to walk close to the walker's legs. She's so happy that she wags her tail the entire walk. She likes to go in the play yard and will play fetch with the ball for a little while but the thing that Mako wants to the most is to show you how much she loves you and get some affection in return. She knows how to "sit" for treats and will take the food gently. Mako can get a little excited when she's happy and will jump up but she is easily corrected and will sit down when told to. She's a smart girl and can be trained not to jump if she's rewarded with a treat. She would do better in a home with children that are 5 years and older.

Mako didn't like the other dogs when she was taken into a play group and would do best as an only dog. If you think Mako would make a good fit in your home, please come and meet her today! She would love to go home.

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
****Please do not send messages to the rescue asking if a dog is still available; if a dog is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO & FAQs BEFORE EMAILING THE RESCUE****

Teeny and Taz are a bonded pair of female dappled chiweenies. They were with their previous owner since 6 weeks old. They are now 7  years old. Their owner took very good care of them and was moving to a place he could not take them. They are spayed and heartworm negative. They are fully housetrained and go to the door when they need to use the restroom. They have the most fun loving and affectionate personalities. They love to play with each other and then sleep on each other. They are very clingy with people and want to follow their people around everywhere. They are eager to be on a lap, and if you stop petting them, they will paw at you to beg for more pets. They are not stranger weary and are outgoing with new friends. They weigh under 10 pounds. 

To apply to adopt this dog, visit www.snarrnortheast.org/applications and submit an application. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING 
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder,  there are sometimes discrepancies between the breed that is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
TO MEET Alpha, PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION TO ADOPT AT www.almosthomeyyc.com. 

*PLEASE NOTE WE ARE LOCATED IN CANADA AND UNABLE TO ADOPT TO ANOTHER COUNTRY.

INFORMATION: Alpha is a 1-1.5 year old Border Collie mix that was found as a stray in Northern Saskatchewan.

TEMPERAMENT: Alpha is an athletic medium size dog. True to his border collie and herding nature he is best suited for an owner with the time and energy to keep him active and mentally stimulated. 

PERSONALITY: Alpha is smart, affectionate and energetic. He will spend hours playing fetch and knows some tricks and basic commands like sit and shake paw. When his is not adequately stimulated he will chew up toys but knows that his bed is not for chewing. He can be dog selective so should always have proper introductions when meeting a new doggie friend. He is a bit jumpy and would likely not be suited for small children that he may knock over in excitement. 

IDEAL HOME: Alpha is searching for an active home, one with a fenced yard for him to run and play is best. He is not suited for condo or apartment living. He would love a home that would be interested in agility training as it would satisfy his needs for mental stimulation.

If you would like to meet Alpha, please fill in an adoption application.

Please note: We apologize for being unable to respond to inquiries about our dogs without an adoption application. Please visit www.almosthomeyyc.com to fill out an application.

animal.description:
Meet Bradley! His brother Cooper has been adopted- together they were the award-winning actor Bradley Cooper! Bradley and Cooper came from Texas as part of BISSELL Pet Foundation's Emergency Hurricane Relief Program.

Meet Bradley! He is 11.5 months and is ready to find his fur-ever home! Bradley is super sweet, fun-loving, and playful! animal.description:
01-24-21 UPDATE: Colt is a really sweet boy who just wants to love you. Treeing walker coonhound Colt is a really sweet boy. He has the best eye contact. He will look at you with his honey brown eyes and you will be in heaven! He really just wants to love you. He could probably be an emotional support dog if he had a patient and diligent trainer. He could never be a dog that goes to hospitals and is a therapy dog because he's too active, but he really connects with humans. He also absolutely loves to run around the backyard with another dog or multiple dogs; it would help him a lot to be adopted to a home with another dog. He would do great with kids because he's really playful. We don't recommend him with young kids because he's big and we don't want them to get knocked down inadvertently. Technically he is a medium-sized dog at 52 pounds, but he has long legs. Thus, Colt is a very fitting name for him. He does gallop about -- he is absolutely beautiful. An adopter returned this dog after 15 minutes because they thought he was too wild in their car. If he were in a crate he wouldn't have been. He also will bay in the right circumstances, so he definitely wouldn't be the right choice for someone who lives in an apartment or lives really close to somebody else. But, he would be absolutely fantastic in a household where there are other hounds so they could just be themselves and be absolutely adorable. To adopt teenaged treeing walker coonhound Colt, please visit our website  www.peace4paws.org and fill out an adoption application. Thank you.  =======================================================   
Colt is a super sweet young Treeing walker coonhound mix who appeared at a KY shelter just before Christmas as a stray. No one claimed him so he spent all of Christmas and New Year’s in the shelter. He just can’t wait to get out and start his new life with his forever family!!! Colt is fifty-two pounds, approximately one year old, and good with dogs. He loves to play with other dogs. By all appearances he seems like he will be a great family dog. We don’t have too much info about whether he needs training in housebreaking or not. We don’t have any specific info on how he is with kids or cats at this time. If more info comes in before he arrives January 10th, we will post it on our Facebook page as soon as we know. We do know that he will be up to date on all his shots, neutered, and microchipped by the time he arrives here. To adopt this handsome hound boy please visit our website www.peace4paws.org and fill out an adoption application. Thank you so much! 


Dog Size Guidelines:
Small: 25 lbs and under (11 kg)
Medium: 26–60 lbs (12 – 27 kg)
Large: 61–100 lbs (28 – 45 kg)

animal.description:
MEET SHADOW!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4114075.

Look at Shadow's smiling face! He's still smiling even though this is his second time at the shelter looking for his furever home and now he's been there for more than 60 days. It should get him down but it doesn't and he's still a happy boy. Shadow loves to go for a walk especially if you walk at a fast pace. Like to walk slower? Then just put a harness on Shadow and he walks at a calm, easy pace. When he went on a day foster trip, the volunteer stated he jumped right in the car and loved to go for a ride. He got a cheeseburger for lunch and ate it gently. On his way back to the shelter, he laid down in the front seat and put his head in the volunteer's lap and licked her hand to thank her for her kindness and his awesome day.

The kind people that found Shadow wandering in their neighborhood said he was potty trained and he knows "sit" for treats. It would be so great if Shadow could find his furever home soon. If you think Shadow would be a good fit in your home, please bring the family and come and meet him today. He would probably do better if he was the only dog in the home, but if you already have a dog, please bring them with you to see if they would do well together.

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
PittieLove Rescue, Inc. a 501c3 orgainization is an all-volunteer, foster home based rescue.

Adoption Fee: $375
Our information is current if you are interested please fill out an adoption form here
http://www.pittieloverescue.org/adoption-application
It is the easiest way to start the communication and adoption process.Meet Fergie! This 4-year old wiggle butt emits magical fibers of love and, like her name, is one fergilicious little lady. And little she is! Fergie is short in stature at 34 compact pounds, but more than makes up for it in her sassy and larger-than-life personality. She is the CEO and founding member of the IBPC (Ittie Bittie Pittie Committee), frozen in time as a perpetual pint-sized puppy. But it's obvious from her condition that someone didn't take very good care of her. She has large scars on her back, leg, and face, possibly from an old burn injury. She was picked up with a raging UTI and her now-shiny coat had likely been urine soaked for quite some time. She has been working on housetraining in her foster home - likely a combination of the UTI and the possibility she was confined and/or not let outside regularly. But this short stack holds no grudges and looooves everyone she meets. And we've promised her it's all unicorns, cupcakes, and sprinkles from this point forward.

Fergie is a miniature munchkin, a sophisticated ewok, and an enchanting mogwai rolled into one. Her stunt doubles literally include Gizmo and Baby Yoda (with the sound effects to match). She's a pro at chirping like a baby bird and is happily inquisitive in her foster home, trotting along to explore every nook and cranny. In fact, you'll likely catch The Dutchess snorting up a storm, canoodling with her favorite humans, or snoozing with her petite pink tongue peeking out from her adorable under bite. So delicious! She loves human companionship and would thrive in a home where she is treated as one of the gangon the couch watching the game, snuggled up in bed for quality cuddle time, and going on adventures with her favorite humans.

Fergie loves to eat and will gobble up and guzzle down virtually anything you put in front of her (except zucchini - that's gross!). Fergie is relaxed around the dogs in her foster home, though she's much more interested in humans and food, and says no thanks to kitties. We suspect she would enjoy being the center of attention. Due to his lack of history, older kids would be best for this loveable lowrider.www.pittieloverescue.org

Please consider a donation so that we may continue the important work we do.

animal.description:
Oreo is a tiny male Papillon that was surrendered to our shelter after his owner passed away.  He’s a cute little fella, and easily fits in your lap at only fourteen pounds.  He has big butterfly ears and a soft fluffy white and black coat.  Oreo really misses his Papa and would love to be in a home again.  He prefers a quiet calm household with someone that is home most of the day.  Oreo is perfect for a senior or family with older children.  He is very affectionate and will form a close bond with you.  Always a gentleman, he is well behaved and calm.  Oreo is housebroken and will need a fenced in yard.  Other than a daily walk, he doesn’t require much exercise.  Oreo spends most of his day blissfully snoozing; content in the knowledge you are near.  He would be perfectly happy as your “one and only” pet but does do well with other calm mature dogs.  If you currently own a dog, we can schedule a meet and greet to check if they are compatible.  Oreo has not been around cats but we can test that for you.  This little dog is really quite special and needs to feel loved again.  If you are looking for a sweet calm companion, Oreo is the perfect dog for you.  

To adopt this pet, Click "More About Us" and then "Adoption Application" to be directed to our online HSNWGA application form.  You will be contacted by our Adoption Coordinator once your application is reviewed and approved.  Due to high volume of applications, we are only able to contact those applicants that best meet the needs of that individual pet.

They are into exactly everything a puppy should want to be into...they know all the ways to get out of the trouble they get into....they clean their bowls....they steal everyone's favorite toys,  but they give them back politely when asked. He can occupy himself with toys and doesn't have to be in the middle of the circus all the time. Unkie will make a great companion!!!

Unkie is up to date on shots and preventatives and is microchipped.  He will be adopted with a neuter agreement due to his size and age.  Unkie's adoption fee is $250 plus any additional donation you feel appropriate.  Our adoption fee is set to a level to make adoptions happen.  They do not cover our costs. All dogs adopted locally through SGDR receive a free six-week session of obedience classes and a lifetime of behavior support through our Project REWARD program with trainer Charlotte Blake.

animal.description:
My life before Peak Lab Rescue was a struggle to say the least. I was on my own and starving for a while. I was caught by animal control and spent a WHOLE MONTH at the shelter. I'm not gonna lie, things were looking pretty bleak for me. Fortunately, I caught the eye of a volunteer from Peak. Next thing I knew, I was in a car on my way to freedom.

My name is FlapJack, but foster family has lots of nicknames for me: Jackjack, Blackjack, Jaxson, Jackie, Handsome, and my personal favorite - "Goodboy. I am around 2 years old and 55 pounds of lanky houndy goofiness. Like a couple of the people in my foster home, I am a gorgeous redhead. I have adored every person I have met and will thump my tail in appreciation whenever I am spoken too. I truly know how lucky I am and am such a happy boy!

 
Things you should know about me:

 ~I am fully recovered from my neuter, microchipped, and up to date with vetting.

~I talk in my sleep. Foster dad LOVES my sounds and likes to play me like the bagpipes sometimes, too.

~I am housebroken. I had one accident due to a new medication, but even with an upset tummy I have made it outside every other time.

~I am crate trained.

~I walk great on a leash.

~I love my foster sibling dogs. Even the grumpy one. I would prefer a home with a friendly big dog like me or some doggy friends I can play with regularly.

~I am very food and affection motivated. I learn quickly when treats or love are involved.

~I love ice cubes. I come running when I hear the ice dispenser.

~I like chicken. Maybe a little too much. I was on my own for a good while and helped myself to someone's yard birds. A guy's gotta eat, right?! I haven't met any cats in my foster home, but they may be too interesting for me. I definitely need a home without chickens.

~I have not been around kids in my foster home. I am probably a bit too clumsy and mouthy to be in a home with small children, but would love to have some dog savvy older kids.

~I love a good dog bed. I have been allowed on the couch by, but generally prefer the dog bed or floor for sleeping at night.

~I enjoy being near my people, but I am not what they call a Velcro dog once I have settled in. I don't mind a little space between us. I do love to cuddle once we get to know each other.

~I love a soft squeaky crinkly toy, but I have to be watched closely with them. I made one "disappear once.

~Although I'm a mostly good boy, I do have a bit of a naughty streak. I need a family with a little bit of a sense of humor to handle things like me stealing a sock or unrolling toilet paper.

I was positive for heartworm when I came to Peak Lab. I have completed treatment and my activity restriction is done. I will just need routine preventatives and follow up.  I should be able to have a normal long healthy active life. I am a moderate energy guy who also knows how to enjoy a long nap. I would love a family that will take me hiking and on adventures and keep training me to be the perfect dog for them. Are you my family? If so, fill out an application right away. Foster mom says I'll be scooped up quickly!
animal.name: Flapjack Wayne
